027/**
028 * A palette of predefined colors as packed RGB floats, the kind {@link ColorTools} works with, plus a way to describe
029 * colors by combinations and adjustments. The description code is probably what you would use this class for; it
030 * revolves around {@link #parseDescription(String)}, which takes a color description String and returns a packed float
031 * color. The color descriptions look like "darker rich mint sage", where the order of the words doesn't matter. They
032 * can optionally include lightness changes (light/dark), and saturation changes (rich/dull), and must include one or
033 * more color names that will be mixed together (repeats are allowed to use a color more heavily). The changes can be
034 * suffixed with "er", "est", or "most", such as "duller", "lightest", or "richmost", to progressively increase their
035 * effect on lightness or saturation.
036 * <br>
037 * The rest of this is about the same as in {@link Palette}.
038 * <br>
039 * You can access colors by their constant name, such as {@code CACTUS}, by the {@link #NAMED} map using
040 * {@code NAMED.get("cactus", 0f)}, or by index in the FloatList called {@link #LIST}. Note that to access a float
041 * color from NAMED, you need to give a default value if the name is not found; {@code 0f} is a good default because it
042 * is used for fully-transparent. You can access the names in a specific order with {@link #NAMES} (which is
043 * alphabetical), {@link #NAMES_BY_HUE} (which is sorted by the hue of the matching color, from red to yellow to blue
044 * (with gray around here) to purple to red again), or {@link #NAMES_BY_LIGHTNESS} (which is sorted by the intensity of
045 * the matching color, from darkest to lightest). Having a name lets you look up the matching color in {@link #NAMED}.
046 */
047public class SimplePalette {
048    /**
049     * You can look up colors by name here; the names are lower-case, and the colors are packed floats in rgba format.
050     */
051    public static final ObjectFloatOrderedMap<String> NAMED = new ObjectFloatOrderedMap<>(60);
052    /**
053     * Stores alternative names for colors in {@link #NAMED}, like "grey" as an alias for {@link #GRAY} or "gold" as an
054     * alias for {@link #SAFFRON}. Currently, the list of aliases is as follows:
055     * <ul>
056     * <li>"grey" maps to {@link #GRAY},</li>
057     * <li>"gold" maps to {@link #SAFFRON},</li>
058     * <li>"puce" maps to {@link #MAUVE},</li>
059     * <li>"sand" maps to {@link #TAN},</li>
060     * <li>"skin" maps to {@link #PEACH},</li>
061     * <li>"coral" maps to {@link #SALMON},</li>
062     * <li>"azure" maps to {@link #SKY}, and</li>
063     * <li>"ocean" maps to {@link #TEAL}, and</li>
064     * <li>"sapphire" maps to {@link #COBALT}.</li>
065     * </ul>
066     * Note that these aliases are not duplicated in {@link #NAMES}, {@link #NAMES_BY_HUE}, or
067     * {@link #NAMES_BY_LIGHTNESS}; they are primarily there so blind attempts to name a color might still work.
068     */
069    public static final ObjectFloatOrderedMap<String> ALIASES = new ObjectFloatOrderedMap<>(10);
070    /**
071     * Lists the packed float color values in this, in no particular order. Does not include duplicates from aliases.
072     */
073    public static final FloatList LIST = new FloatList(50);

684    /**
685     * All names for colors in this palette, with grayscale first, then sorted by hue from red to yellow to green to
686     * blue. You can fetch the corresponding packed float color by looking up a name in {@link #NAMED}.
687     */
688    public static final ObjectList<String> NAMES_BY_HUE = new ObjectList<>(NAMES);
689    /**
690     * The packed IPT float colors that correspond to items in {@link #NAMES_BY_HUE}, with the same order.
691     */
692    public static final FloatList COLORS_BY_HUE = new FloatList(NAMES_BY_HUE.size());
693    /**
694     * All names for colors in this palette, sorted by lightness from black to white. You can fetch the
695     * corresponding packed float color by looking up a name in {@link #NAMED}.
696     */
697    public static final ObjectList<String> NAMES_BY_LIGHTNESS = new ObjectList<>(NAMES);
698    static {
699        NAMES_BY_HUE.sort((o1, o2) -> {
700            final float c1 = NAMED.get(o1), c2 = NAMED.get(o2);
701            final float s1 = saturation(c1), s2 = saturation(c2);
702            // a packed float color with a sign bit of 0 (a non-negative number) is mostly transparent.
703            // this also considers 0x80000000 transparent, but it's almost at the threshold.
704            if(c1 >= 0f) return -10000;
705            else if(c2 >= 0f) return 10000;
706            else if(s1 <= 0.05f && s2 > 0.05f)
707                return -1000;
708            else if(s1 > 0.05f && s2 <= 0.05f)
709                return 1000;
710            else if(s1 <= 0.05f && s2 <= 0.05f)
711                return (int)Math.signum(lightness(c1) - lightness(c2));
712            else
713                return 2 * (int)Math.signum(hue(c1) - hue(c2))
714                        + (int)Math.signum(lightness(c1) - lightness(c2));
715        });
716        for(String name : NAMES_BY_HUE) {
717            COLORS_BY_HUE.add(NAMED.get(name));
718        }
719        NAMES_BY_LIGHTNESS.sort((o1, o2) -> Float.compare(lightness(NAMED.get(o1)), lightness(NAMED.get(o2))));
720    }

724    /**
725     * Parses a color description and returns the approximate color it describes, as a packed RGBA float color.
726     * Color descriptions consist of one or more alphabetical words, separated by non-alphanumeric characters (typically
727     * spaces and/or hyphens, though the underscore is treated as a letter). Any word that is the name of a color in
728     * this palette will be looked up in {@link #NAMED} and tracked; if there is more than one of these color name
729     * words, the colors will be mixed using {@link FloatColors#unevenMix(float[], int, int)}, or if there is just one
730     * color name word, then the corresponding color will be used. A number can be present after a color name (separated
731     * by any non-alphanumeric character(s) other than the underscore); if so, it acts as a positive weight for that
732     * color name when mixed with other named colors. The recommended separator between a color name and its weight is
733     * the char {@code '^'}, but other punctuation like {@code ':'} is equally valid. You can also repeat a color name
734     * to increase its weight. You may use a decimal point in weights to make them floats.
735     * <br>
736     * The special adjectives "light" and "dark" change the lightness of the described color; likewise, "rich" and
737     * "dull" change the saturation (how different the color is from grayscale). All of these adjectives can have "-er"
738     * or "-est" appended to make their effect twice or three times as strong. Technically, the chars appended to an
739     * adjective don't matter, only their count, so "lightaa" is the same as "lighter" and "richcat" is the same as
740     * "richest". There's an unofficial fourth level as well, used when any 4 characters are appended to an adjective
741     * (as in "darkmost"); it has four times the effect of the original adjective. There are also the adjectives
742     * "bright" (equivalent to "light rich"), "pale" ("light dull"), "deep" ("dark rich"), and "weak" ("dark dull").
743     * These can be amplified like the other four, except that "pale" goes to "paler", "palest", and then to
744     * "palemax" or (its equivalent) "palemost", where only the word length is checked. The case of adjectives doesn't
745     * matter here; they can be all-caps, all lower-case, or mixed-case without issues. The names of colors, however,
746     * are case-sensitive, because you can combine other named color palettes with the one here, and at least in one
747     * common situation (merging libGDX Colors with the palette here), the other palette uses all-caps names only.
748     * <br>
749     * If part of a color name or adjective is invalid, it is not considered; if the description is empty or fully
750     * invalid, this returns the float color {@code 0f}, or fully transparent black.
751     * <br>
752     * Examples of valid descriptions include "blue", "dark green", "duller red", "peach pink", "indigo purple mauve",
753     * "lightest richer apricot-olive", "bright magenta", "palest cyan blue", "deep fern black", "weakmost celery",
754     * "red^3 orange", and "dark deep blue^7 cyan^3".
755     * <br>
756     * This overload always reads the whole String provided.
757     *
758     * @param description a color description, as a String matching the above format
759     * @return a packed RGBA float color as described
760     */
761    public static float parseDescription(final String description) {
762        return parseDescription(description, 0, description.length());

764    /**
765     * Parses a color description and returns the approximate color it describes, as a packed RGBA float color.
766     * Color descriptions consist of one or more alphabetical words, separated by non-alphanumeric characters (typically
767     * spaces and/or hyphens, though the underscore is treated as a letter). Any word that is the name of a color in
768     * this palette will be looked up in {@link #NAMED} and tracked; if there is more than one of these color name
769     * words, the colors will be mixed using {@link FloatColors#unevenMix(float[], int, int)}, or if there is just one
770     * color name word, then the corresponding color will be used. A number can be present after a color name (separated
771     * by any non-alphanumeric character(s) other than the underscore); if so, it acts as a positive weight for that
772     * color name when mixed with other named colors. The recommended separator between a color name and its weight is
773     * the char {@code '^'}, but other punctuation like {@code ':'} is equally valid. You can also repeat a color name
774     * to increase its weight. You may use a decimal point in weights to make them floats.
775     * <br>
776     * The special adjectives "light" and "dark" change the lightness of the described color; likewise, "rich" and
777     * "dull" change the saturation (how different the color is from grayscale). All of these adjectives can have "-er"
778     * or "-est" appended to make their effect twice or three times as strong. Technically, the chars appended to an
779     * adjective don't matter, only their count, so "lightaa" is the same as "lighter" and "richcat" is the same as
780     * "richest". There's an unofficial fourth level as well, used when any 4 characters are appended to an adjective
781     * (as in "darkmost"); it has four times the effect of the original adjective. There are also the adjectives
782     * "bright" (equivalent to "light rich"), "pale" ("light dull"), "deep" ("dark rich"), and "weak" ("dark dull").
783     * These can be amplified like the other four, except that "pale" goes to "paler", "palest", and then to
784     * "palemax" or (its equivalent) "palemost", where only the word length is checked. The case of adjectives doesn't
785     * matter here; they can be all-caps, all lower-case, or mixed-case without issues. The names of colors, however,
786     * are case-sensitive, because you can combine other named color palettes with the one here, and at least in one
787     * common situation (merging libGDX Colors with the palette here), the other palette uses all-caps names only.
788     * <br>
789     * If part of a color name or adjective is invalid, it is not considered; if the description is empty or fully
790     * invalid, this returns the float color {@code 0f}, or fully transparent black.
791     * <br>
792     * Examples of valid descriptions include "blue", "dark green", "duller red", "peach pink", "indigo purple mauve",
793     * "lightest richer apricot-olive", "bright magenta", "palest cyan blue", "deep fern black", "weakmost celery",
794     * "red^3 orange", and "dark deep blue^7 cyan^3".
795     * <br>
796     * This overload lets you specify a
797     * starting index in {@code description} to read from and a maximum {@code length} to read before stopping. If
798     * {@code length} is negative, this reads the rest of {@code description} after {@code start}.
799     *
800     * @param description a color description, as a String matching the above format
801     * @param start the first character index of the description to read from
802     * @param length how much of description to attempt to parse; if negative, this parses until the end
803     * @return a packed RGBA float color as described
804     */
805    public static float parseDescription(final String description, int start, int length) {
806        float lightness = 0f, saturation = 0f;
807        final String[] terms = description.substring(start,
808                        length < 0 ? description.length() - start : Math.min(description.length(), start + length))
809                .split("[^a-zA-Z0-9_.]+");
810        mixing.clear();
811        for (int i = 0; i < terms.length; i++) {
812            String term = terms[i];
813            if (term == null || term.isEmpty()) continue;
814            final int len = term.length();
815            switch (term.charAt(0)) {
816                case 'L':
817                case 'l':
818                    if (len > 2 && (term.charAt(2) == 'g' || term.charAt(2) == 'G')) { // light
819                        switch (len) {
820                            case 9:
821                                lightness +=  0.20f;
822                            case 8:
823                                lightness +=  0.20f;
824                            case 7:
825                                lightness +=  0.20f;
826                            case 5:
827                                lightness +=  0.20f;
828                                continue;
829                        }
830                    }
831                    mixing.add(NAMED.get(term), 1);
832                    break;
833                case 'B':
834                case 'b':
835                    if (len > 3 && (term.charAt(3) == 'g' || term.charAt(3) == 'G')) { // bright
836                        switch (len) {
837                            case 10:
838                                lightness +=  0.20f;
839                                saturation += 00.20000f;
840                            case 9:
841                                lightness +=  0.20f;
842                                saturation += 00.2000f;
843                            case 8:
844                                lightness +=  0.20f;
845                                saturation += 00.200f;
846                            case 6:
847                                lightness +=  0.20f;
848                                saturation += 00.20f;
849                                continue;
850                        }
851                    }
852                    mixing.add(NAMED.get(term), 1);
853                    break;
854                case 'P':
855                case 'p':
856                    if (len > 2 && (term.charAt(2) == 'l' || term.charAt(2) == 'L')) { // pale
857                        switch (len) {
858                            case 8: // palemost
859                            case 7: // palerer
860                                lightness +=  0.20f;
861                                saturation -= 00.20000f;
862                            case 6: // palest
863                                lightness +=  0.20f;
864                                saturation -= 00.2000f;
865                            case 5: // paler
866                                lightness +=  0.20f;
867                                saturation -= 00.200f;
868                            case 4: // pale
869                                lightness +=  0.20f;
870                                saturation -= 00.20f;
871                                continue;
872                        }
873                    }
874                    mixing.add(NAMED.get(term), 1);
875                    break;
876                case 'W':
877                case 'w':
878                    if (len > 3 && (term.charAt(3) == 'k' || term.charAt(3) == 'K')) { // weak
879                        switch (len) {
880                            case 8:
881                                lightness -=  0.20f;
882                                saturation -= 00.20000f;
883                            case 7:
884                                lightness -=  0.20f;
885                                saturation -= 00.2000f;
886                            case 6:
887                                lightness -=  0.20f;
888                                saturation -= 00.200f;
889                            case 4:
890                                lightness -=  0.20f;
891                                saturation -= 00.20f;
892                                continue;
893                        }
894                    }
895                    mixing.add(NAMED.get(term), 1);
896                    break;
897                case 'R':
898                case 'r':
899                    if (len > 1 && (term.charAt(1) == 'i' || term.charAt(1) == 'I')) { // rich
900                        switch (len) {
901                            case 8:
902                                saturation += 00.20000f;
903                            case 7:
904                                saturation += 00.2000f;
905                            case 6:
906                                saturation += 00.200f;
907                            case 4:
908                                saturation += 00.20f;
909                                continue;
910                        }
911                    }
912                    mixing.add(NAMED.get(term), 1);
913                    break;
914                case 'D':
915                case 'd':
916                    if (len > 1 && (term.charAt(1) == 'a' || term.charAt(1) == 'A')) { // dark
917                        switch (len) {
918                            case 8:
919                                lightness -=  0.20f;
920                            case 7:
921                                lightness -=  0.20f;
922                            case 6:
923                                lightness -=  0.20f;
924                            case 4:
925                                lightness -=  0.20f;
926                                continue;
927                        }
928                    } else if (len > 1 && (term.charAt(1) == 'u' || term.charAt(1) == 'U')) { // dull
929                        switch (len) {
930                            case 8:
931                                saturation -= 00.20000f;
932                            case 7:
933                                saturation -= 00.2000f;
934                            case 6:
935                                saturation -= 00.200f;
936                            case 4:
937                                saturation -= 00.20f;
938                                continue;
939                        }
940                    } else if (len > 3 && (term.charAt(3) == 'p' || term.charAt(3) == 'P')) { // deep
941                        switch (len) {
942                            case 8:
943                                lightness -=  0.20f;
944                                saturation += 00.20000f;
945                            case 7:
946                                lightness -=  0.20f;
947                                saturation += 00.2000f;
948                            case 6:
949                                lightness -=  0.20f;
950                                saturation += 00.200f;
951                            case 4:
952                                lightness -=  0.20f;
953                                saturation += 00.20f;
954                                continue;
955                        }
956                    }
957                    mixing.add(NAMED.get(term), 1);
958                    break;
959                case '0':
960                case '1':
961                case '2':
962                case '3':
963                case '4':
964                case '5':
965                case '6':
966                case '7':
967                case '8':
968                case '9':
969                    if(mixing.size() >= 2) {
970                        float num = 1;
971                        try {
972                            num = Float.parseFloat(term);
973                        } catch (NullPointerException | NumberFormatException ignored) {
974                        }
975                        mixing.set((mixing.size() & -2) - 1, num);
976                    }
977                    break;
978                default:
979                    mixing.add(NAMED.get(term), 1);
980                    break;
981            }
982        }
983        if(mixing.size() < 2) return 0f;
984
985        float result = unevenMix(mixing.items, 0, mixing.size());
986        if(result == 0f) return result;
987
988        if(lightness > 0) result = ColorTools.lighten(result, lightness);
989        else if(lightness < 0) result = ColorTools.darken(result, -lightness);
990
991        if(saturation > 0) result = ColorTools.enrich(result, saturation);
992        else if(saturation < 0) result = ColorTools.dullen(result, -saturation);
993
994        return result;
995    }

1051    /**
1052     * Given a color as a packed RGBA float, this finds the closest description it can to match the given color while
1053     * using at most {@code mixCount} colors to mix in. You should only use small numbers for mixCount, like 1 to 3;
1054     * this can take quite a while to run otherwise. This returns a String description that can be passed to
1055     * {@link #parseDescription(String)}. It is likely that this will use very contrasting colors if mixCount is 2 or
1056     * greater and the color to match is desaturated or brownish.
1057     * @param rgb a packed RGBA float color to attempt to match
1058     * @param mixCount how many color names this will use in the returned description
1059     * @return a description that can be fed to {@link #parseDescription(String)} to get a similar color
1060     */
1061    public static String bestMatch(final float rgb, int mixCount) {
1062        mixCount = Math.max(1, mixCount);
1063        float oklab = com.github.tommyettinger.colorful.pure.oklab.ColorTools.fromRGBA(rgb);
1064        float bestDistance = Float.POSITIVE_INFINITY;
1065        final int paletteSize = namesByHue.size(), colorTries = (int)Math.pow(paletteSize, mixCount), totalTries = colorTries * 81;
1066        final float targetL = com.github.tommyettinger.colorful.pure.oklab.ColorTools.channelL(oklab),
1067                targetA = com.github.tommyettinger.colorful.pure.oklab.ColorTools.channelA(oklab),
1068                targetB = com.github.tommyettinger.colorful.pure.oklab.ColorTools.channelB(oklab);
1069        mixing.clear();
1070        for (int i = 0; i < mixCount; i++) {
1071            mixing.add(colorsByHue.get(0));
1072        }
1073        int bestCode = 0;
1074        for (int c = 0; c < totalTries; c++) {
1075            for (int i = 0, e = 1; i < mixCount; i++, e *= paletteSize) {
1076                mixing.set(i, colorsByHue.get((c / e) % paletteSize));
1077            }
1078            int idxL = ((c / colorTries) % 9 - 4), idxS = (c / (colorTries * 9) - 4);
1079
1080            float result = FloatColors.mix(mixing.items, 0, mixCount);
1081            if(idxL > 0) result = ColorTools.lighten(result, 0.20f * idxL);
1082            else if(idxL < 0) result = ColorTools.darken(result, -0.20f * idxL);
1083
1084            if(idxS > 0) result = (ColorTools.enrich(result, idxS * 0.200f));
1085            else if(idxS < 0) result = ColorTools.dullen(result, idxS * -0.200f);
1086
1087            oklab = com.github.tommyettinger.colorful.pure.oklab.ColorTools.fromRGBA(result);
1088
1089            final float dL = com.github.tommyettinger.colorful.pure.oklab.ColorTools.channelL(oklab) - targetL;
1090            final float dA = com.github.tommyettinger.colorful.pure.oklab.ColorTools.channelA(oklab) - targetA;
1091            final float dB = com.github.tommyettinger.colorful.pure.oklab.ColorTools.channelB(oklab) - targetB;
1092            if(bestDistance > (bestDistance = Math.min(dL * dL + dA * dA + dB * dB, bestDistance)))
1093                bestCode = c;
1094        }
1095
1096        StringBuilder description = new StringBuilder(combinedAdjectives[(bestCode / colorTries)]);
1097        for (int i = 0, e = 1; i < mixCount; e *= paletteSize) {
1098            description.append(namesByHue.get((bestCode / e) % paletteSize));
1099            if(++i < mixCount)
1100                description.append(' ');
1101        }
1102        return description.toString();
1103    }
